column95:
I grew up in a a family that went to Church for major holidays and did not believe in Christ or God, but did not disbelieve either. And then during my undergraduate degree, my first year roommate and I became close friends. And this is where it gets interesting, she was Christian and invited me to come out to a Christian group on campus.  I came to know Christ through the people of the club and after a few months of hanging out with the power to change group I gave my life to Jesus Christ our Lord and savior. I got baptized the following year (after understanding what it meant to be reborn and fully surrender to and obey God's will for us).

Since then I have gone on a mission's trip to the university's of Denmark to share the word with the students, joined children's ministry (and served in nursery ever since). In my second year of university God told me to read and study the Bible in 90 days...And I said yes. Boy was that ever a whirlwind adventure. Also, I have also met and married my husband at that same Christian group. He also serves here at sanctus and has been a member since it was steeple hill.
Anyway, lately I have been working and learning to hear God's discernment in my career and work life since I have recently graduated from my masters. He is teaching me patience and to trust in His plan for me. I have also been reading Job and figuring out what it means to fully trust in God and believe in His plan for us, regardless of how the situation currently looks or feels to me.

column95: Hello, my name is Matthew Cechetto. I am 12 years old. When I was younger, I was always afraid of something happening in the night. Born on 21st February 1983 in a Christian family, I was bought up in the fear of God by my godly parents. Early into my childhood due to the financial circumstances in our family, my father had to leave India and take up a job in Saudi Arabia. Therefore, my mother played a key role in my upbringing. 

At the age of three, I suffered from a life-threatening disease, Jaundice (Yellow fever). One night after being discharged from the hospital, my health started to deteriorate, and finally at twelve, I stopped breathing. I was dead. The family panicked and there was a lot of mourning as the child was dead. Somehow during that time my mother mustered the courage and asked everyone to vacate the room. She went on he knees and prayed earnestly and with deep conviction, believing that it is only God who can restore life. 

She prayed in faith and said, Ã¢ÂÂLord if you give me my son back, then I will raise him up in your ways and when he grows up and is of knowledgeable age, I will teach him your ways and your purpose to live and testify your goodness, and dedicate his life towards serving you.

As Job prayed, she prayed and said, The Lord has given, the Lord has taken. Let the name of the Lord be glorified. May your will be done. As she finished her prayer the life that left me was restored and I revived. 

In my teenage years, I grew apart from God and started following my own heart. I was a real pain to my mother. She had come to a point where she regretted asking the Lord to restore my life.

One summer holiday I attended a youth camp (ICPF Ã¢ÂÂ Inter-colligate Prayer Fellowship) where the Lord touched my heart and I was convicted of my sins. The message by the preacher did strike a chord. I dedicated my life to Christ and accepted the Lord as my personal savior on June 15, 1994.

My relatives shammed me as I wanted to serve the Lord. They did not understand why someone of my age would want to be involved in religious activity. They thought that I was doing poorly in my studies and thus was making an excuse by opting to serve the Lord. I did fairly in my studies. I trusted in God to help me in things that were difficult for me. In the year 1996, on August 11, I decided to take water baptism. It was truly a blessed day as I recall. Thereafter in another 2 months' time during a fasting prayer at our home, I was filled with the baptism of the Holy Spirit. 

Since then I have been actively involved in church affairs. I finished my Schooling in 2001. The Lord helped me to complete my graduation. I did my majors in Political Science and along with that did my software engineering. I worked with a Christian Organization Ã¢ÂÂAwana Clubs IndiaÃ¢ÂÂ for 2 years. In the year 2006, I applied for a residential course in Union Biblical Seminary for my bachelorÃ¢ÂÂs in divinity (B.D) and graduated in the year 2010. I worked as an Associate pastor with Apostolic Faith Church from 2010 to 2017 December, after which the Lord moved us to Canada in 2018. In the meantime was involved with a Bible Translation Agency that was a subsidiary of Wycliffe Associates from 2011-2017. I was involved with Apostolic Faith Church, New Delhi, India, in various roles. I was a Sunday school teacher, a worship leader, and a teacher, teaching the new believers the essentials of sound doctrines. 
 
Currently, in Canada, I am working with an US based organization known as unfoldingWord, as Tech Support and Training personal. I attend Sanctus Church since June 2019. I have 2 Children; my son, Jeremiah is 10 Years old and my daughter, Joanna is 6 Years old. My wife Bincy and I have been married for the last 13 years. She is also working with unfoldingWord since April 2020. We are a missionary family serving the Lord in the world of Bible translation.

Hope that this testimony encourages you to acknowledge that it is only Christ within us that can change any situation around for His Glory.

column95: I was born and raised in Mumbai, India in a Christian family to parents who came to the saving grace of Jesus Christ from a Hindu background a few years prior to my birth. Both my Mom and Dad had encountered supernatural experiences and healings which led them to the love of Christ. Growing up, my parents instilled in my two elders sisters and me the importance of loving and seeking God's kingdom first over everything. My parents and my Sunday school teachers played an integral part in my walk with Christ. I loved my church family and was actively involved in Sunday school activities and the church choir. At the age of 12, I accepted Jesus as my Lord and Saviour during one of Sunday school classes  and soon got baptized. From an early age I desired to serve the Lord and had committed to God that I would serve Him wherever he led me. I completed my Bachelors in Technology and soon after married my husband Jobby who also had a heart for full-time ministry. My husband and I have been married for the last 13 years and are blessed with two wonderful children Jeremiah(10) and Joanna(6). We served in an independent local church in New Delhi called Apostolic Faith Church where my husband served as assistant pastor till 2018. While I served in God's kingdom, I was also able to successfully pursue a career in Product Management and I worked in multiple product management roles in American Express India and Canada branches.In January 2018, God opened ways for us to take up permanent residence in Canada and we moved in this new country three years ago. My husband has been engaged in Bible translation ministries for over 10 years and while I passively supported his work through prayers, it was only recently that I took a deeper interest in learning more about the Bible translation efforts globally. In 2020, I decided to quit my job at Amex and joined the Bible translation organization in the role of a project manager and I'm currently involved in multiple Bible translation software development projects. My husband and I have been hosting a Connect group every other Wednesday for the last one year and we've loved the experience of growing and learning together with new friends. It's been a joy to serve the Lord together as a family in various roles and be part of the amazing work God's doing through people, organizations and as a church. It is is our desire to continue to serve God and his people wherever He leads us for the glory and the extension of His Kingdom.

column95: My name is Samantha Lalli and I am a wife and mother of 2 girls, and a stepmom of 2. Raised as a Catholic, I went through the various rituals growing up. I have always felt a longing to connect with God, yet never really knew how. I tried several denominations over the years, desperately trying to seek Him, yet never really did. COVID was a real turning point for me. For the first time in a long time, I had time to sit and reflect. This reflection turned into some soul searching. God had blessed me with a wonderful husband and children, however, spiritually I knew something was missing and I wanted to grow in my faith. I made a commitment to spend a few hours everyday with Him while my girls did online school. Whether it was reading my study Bible, watching various sermons, or just time in prayer and solitude. As I began my studies, I began to realize the magnitude of what Jesus did for me when he died on the cross, and the gift of salvation he offers. I had never really understood the depth of this. The more time I spent with Him, the more time I wanted to spend, and the connection I had always yearned for was beginning to form. Now in my daily life, I turn to Him daily for guidance and strength. I am grounded by His word, and take comfort in Him. My journey would not have been the same without my mentor and friend, Cora, who has always lovingly guided me towards the Lord, and offered her support. I also want to thank my family for always supporting me in my journey, as it has become our journey together. So I am excited today to be baptized and share my love for Jesus with everyone, and declare Him as my Lord and Saviour.

column95: Hi, my name is Alia and I am 18 years old. When I reflect on my life I see it as a rollercoaster. As a kid I listened to the condescending voices around me that told me I was not smart enough, I had no future and I needed to grow up. I felt broken by the words that were constantly thrown at me and the number of times I attempted to please family so they would love me. As I got older many relationships around me crumbled and it made me not recognize myself. I felt alone. One Sunday I joined my Mom in watching an online service here at Sanctus. It was eye-opening but I could not understand how religion even worked. My whole life I have been blamed for things and felt not worthy of a lot, so it confused me to hear how Jesus is so loving. It was at one service when Jon welcomed all skeptics or non-believers to welcome Jesus into their lives, so I did. This warmth of energy entered me and overtook the coldness inside me. Today when I reflect on my life,  I do not feel saddened by the life I was given but blessed to have it. As I now know that even on the bad days I will never be alone and Jesus will always be there loving me, and guiding me. I finally say that I finally know who I am, (a child of God). I want to thank my Mom for everything in my life, being there for me when I fall, laughing with me, celebrating achievements, teaching me about faith, and loving me as your own. Also, my Alpha group. IÃ¢ÂÂm here today to let you know that Jesus Christ is my lord and savior.

column95: I learned about Jesus as a child.  My parents took me to Sunday school each week at the United Church.  Sadly, they did not have relationship with God.  I guess it was the thing to do back then.  I experienced Jesus' love for me when I received a toy record player and a record that played Jesus loves Me on it.  I think I was around 5 years old when I first believed Jesus was my Savior.  In grade one my teacher taught us the Lord's prayer, explaining each sentence and reminding us that we are talking to God when we pray it - it is not a repetition, He is listening.  My parents had me baby baptized, and I confirmed my belief in Jesus and my desire to follow Him at 13 in the United Church.  I grew up talking to God and reading His word.  I would confide in Him if I was upset about something and He would make me feel better.  I would pray to Him when scared or if I did something wrong to ask for forgiveness.  As my family one by one stopped going to church (except my now 101 year old Grandma) I continued and enjoyed serving and going to youth group.  As a young adult I had a few years in University where I strayed in my walk with God.  At age  20, I repented, recommitted my life and experienced being filled with the love of God through His Holy Spirit and was baptized the next year.
